	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b></b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />This would be caused by either RF or composite output noise, or possibly by NTSC or PAL "fun".

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>tepples</b> [ Sat Mar 07, 2009 3:14 pm ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b></b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />If the bricks of SMB1 1-2 look really jagged, you're seeing the chroma bleeding into the luma. The <a href="http://nesdevwiki.org/wiki/NTSC_Video" class="postlink">NES PPU's NTSC video encoder</a> takes some shortcuts to save die size (and therefore cost), and they cause the luma and chroma to bleed into each other.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
